Note:
Ruby Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the Ruby translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    Ruby source
      -> ruby_lexer   (tokenize: names, keywords, numbers, strings, symbols, operators)
      -> ruby_parser  (build Ruby AST: def, if/elsif/else, blocks, assignments,
                       method calls, arrays, hashes, expressions with Ruby precedence)
      -> ruby_to_hir  (lower Ruby AST to the canonical hir_nodes producer model)
      -> hir_to_ruby  (emit HIR back to valid Ruby text)
      -> re-lex / re-parse / re-to_hir of the emitted text
      -> structural HIR equality on the key constructs

The probe feeds a representative Ruby program that exercises every major construct
the task requires:

  - a def with params and a return       (def add(a, b) ... return ... end)
  - an if/elsif/else/end                  (if total > 10 ... elsif ... else ... end)
  - an .each do |x| ... end block         (items.each do |x| ... end)
  - a multiple assignment                 (a, b = 1, 2)
  - a method call                         (puts total)
  - an array + hash literal               ([1, 2, 3] ; { name: "ruby", n: 3 })

It lowers the source to HIR1, asserts on HIR1 that the module declarations carry a
function node named "add" with two parameters, an if/elsif/else, a call carrying a
block, a multiple-assignment block, a method call, and the array/hash literals;
emits HIR1 back to Ruby text, re-runs the whole pipeline on the emitted text to
HIR2, and asserts HIR2 is STRUCTURALLY EQUAL to HIR1 on those same key constructs.
Structural equality (node-kind tags plus identifying payloads such as method name,
parameter count, control-flow kinds, block parameter, call target, and array/hash
element counts) is the correct semantic-equivalence check because the emitter
re-indents and normalises whitespace while the meaning is identical.

The Ruby HIR node model is the canonical hir_nodes producer surface: every node is
an int-tagged record read via hir_node_type (the kind) and the hir_get_* accessors
(structural fields). This probe reads HIR fields via those same accessors the
frontend emits and the backend consumes.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/ruby/ruby_lexer.runa" as RubyLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/ruby/ruby_parser.runa" as RubyParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/ruby/ruby_to_hir.runa" as RubyFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/ruby/hir_to_ruby.runa" as RubyBackend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Each round of the probe runs the identical front-of-pipeline (lex -> parse ->
to_hir). Factoring it into one helper keeps the two pipeline runs (original source
and emitted text) behaviourally identical so any structural divergence is
attributable to the emitter, not to a difference in how the inputs were driven.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Builds a lexer over the source, wraps it in a parser (which pre-tokenizes), drives
a full parse to the Ruby AST_PROGRAM root, then lowers the AST to HIR via
translate_ruby_to_hir and returns the HIR module. Returns 0 if any stage yields 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_ruby_lexer from RubyLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_ruby_parser from RubyParser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse_ruby from RubyParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc translate_ruby_to_hir from RubyFrontend with ast
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Ruby frontend adds each top-level statement DIRECTLY as a module declaration
(unlike the Lua frontend, which wraps the whole file body in one block). To locate
a construct by kind we read the module declarations and linear-scan for the first
declaration whose hir_node_type matches the requested kind. Linear scan (rather
than fixed index) is robust to the frontend reordering or interleaving statements.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reads hir_get_declarations(module) and scans for hir_node_type == kind. Returns the
first match or 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "find_decl" takes module as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let decl_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl
        If decl_kind is equal to kind:
            Return decl
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A method-call statement is wrapped by the frontend in an expression statement
whose inner expression is the HIR call. This helper scans the module declarations
for the first expression statement whose inner expression is a call expression and
returns that call node, so the probe can assert on the call directly.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Scans declarations; for each HIR_EXPR_STMT reads the inner expression via
hir_get_expression_statement_expr and returns it when its kind is HIR_CALL_EXPR.
Returns 0 if none found.
@End Implementation
Process called "find_call_stmt" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let decl_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl
        If decl_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_EXPR_STMT:
            Let inner be proc hir_get_expression_statement_expr from HIR with decl
            Let inner_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with inner
            If inner_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
                Return inner
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A multiple-assignment lowers to a HIR block tagged "ruby_multiple_assign". This
helper scans the module declarations for the first such block so the probe can
assert the parallel-assignment structure round-trips.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_multiple_assign" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let decl_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl
        If decl_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK:
            Let tag be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl, "ruby_multiple_assign"
            Let is_multi be proc string_equals from StringCore with tag, "true"
            If is_multi is equal to 1:
                Return decl
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two Ruby programs are structurally equal on a construct when both HIR projections
expose the same node-kind tag. Comparing kinds (and, for named constructs, the
identifying payload) rather than byte text is whitespace-insensitive, proving
round-trip fidelity without being defeated by the emitter's re-indenting.
@End Reasoning
Process called "same_kind" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ka be proc hir_node_type from HIR with a
    Let kb be proc hir_node_type from HIR with b
    If ka is equal to kb:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The first argument carrying the call's trailing block is tagged "ruby_call_block".
This helper returns that block (a HIR lambda) from a call node so the probe can
assert the .each do |x| ... end block parameter round-trips.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_call_block" takes call_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If call_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let args be proc hir_get_positional_args from HIR with call_node
    If args is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with args
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let arg be proc list_get from List with args, i
        Let tag be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with arg, "ruby_call_block"
        Let is_block be proc string_equals from StringCore with tag, "true"
        If is_block is equal to 1:
            Return arg
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The first non-block argument of a call is its receiver-independent argument list
head; for "[1,2,3].each" the call target is a member expression on an array
literal. This helper returns the call's callee so the probe can assert the call
target round-trips as a member access.
@End Reasoning
Process called "call_callee_kind" takes call_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If call_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let callee be proc hir_get_call_callee from HIR with call_node
    Return proc hir_node_type from HIR with callee
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "Ruby translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative program: a def with params + return, an if/elsif/else/end, an
    .each do |x| block, a multiple assignment, a method call, and an array + hash
    literal. Newlines separate the statements.
    :End Note
    Let source be "def add(a, b)\nreturn a + b\nend\ntotal = add(3, 4)\nif total > 10\nputs total\nelsif total > 5\nputs total\nelse\nputs 0\nend\nnums = [1, 2, 3]\nnums.each do |x|\nputs x\nend\na, b = 1, 2\nputs total\nopts = { name: \"ruby\", n: 3 }\n"

    Note: --- Stage 0-2: source -> HIR (lex, parse, lower) ---
    Let lexer be proc create_ruby_lexer from RubyLexer with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "lexer created", lexer

    Let parser be proc create_ruby_parser from RubyParser with lexer
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "parser created", parser

    Let ast be proc parse_ruby from RubyParser with parser
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "parser produced Ruby AST", ast

    Let hir1 be proc translate_ruby_to_hir from RubyFrontend with ast
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "frontend produced HIR module", hir1

    Note: Module must expose a non-empty declaration list (the top-level statements).
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR module has declarations", declarations
    Let decl_count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "module has several top-level declarations", decl_count, 5

    Note: --- def: located by kind, name + param count checked ---
    Let func_node be proc find_decl with hir1, HIR.HIR_FUNCTION
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "function node present", func_node
    Let func_name be proc hir_get_function_name from HIR with func_node
    Let func_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with func_name, "add"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function name is 'add'", func_name_ok, 1
    Let func_params be proc hir_get_parameters from HIR with func_node
    Let func_param_list be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with func_params
    Let func_param_count be proc list_length from List with func_param_list
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function 'add' has 2 parameters", func_param_count, 2

    Note: --- if/elsif/else: located by kind, condition + else present ---
    Let if_node be proc find_decl with hir1, HIR.HIR_IF
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "if statement node present", if_node
    Let if_cond be proc hir_get_if_condition from HIR with if_node
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "if statement has a condition", if_cond
    Let if_cond_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with if_cond
    Let if_cond_is_binary be 0
    If if_cond_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPR:
        Set if_cond_is_binary to 1
    End If
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "if condition is a binary expression", if_cond_is_binary, 1
    Let if_else be proc hir_get_if_else from HIR with if_node
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "if statement has an elsif/else tail", if_else
    Note: the tail is the elsif (a nested HIR if tagged ruby_elsif).
    Let elsif_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with if_else
    Let elsif_is_if be 0
    If elsif_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_IF:
        Set elsif_is_if to 1
    End If
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "elsif tail is a nested if", elsif_is_if, 1

    Note: --- .each do |x| block: a call carrying a block with one block param ---
    Let call_block_stmt be proc find_call_with_block with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "call carrying a block present", call_block_stmt
    Let block_node be proc find_call_block with call_block_stmt
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "trailing block present on call", block_node
    Let block_params be proc hir_get_lambda_parameters from HIR with block_node
    Let block_param_list be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with block_params
    Let block_param_count be proc list_length from List with block_param_list
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "block has one parameter |x|", block_param_count, 1
    Let each_callee_kind be proc call_callee_kind with call_block_stmt
    Let each_is_member be 0
    If each_callee_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPR:
        Set each_is_member to 1
    End If
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "block call target is a member access", each_is_member, 1

    Note: --- multiple assignment: a block tagged ruby_multiple_assign, two targets ---
    Let multi_node be proc find_multiple_assign with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "multiple-assignment node present", multi_node
    Let multi_stmts be proc hir_get_block_statements from HIR with multi_node
    Let multi_count be proc list_length from List with multi_stmts
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "multiple assignment has 2 targets", multi_count, 2

    Note: --- method call: an expression statement wrapping a call ---
    Let call_node be proc find_call_stmt with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "method call node present", call_node

    Note: --- array + hash literals: a variable's initializer is a list / map ---
    Let array_found be proc find_initializer_kind with hir1, HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "array literal initializer present", array_found
    Let array_elems be proc hir_get_list_elements from HIR with array_found
    Let array_count be proc list_length from List with array_elems
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "array literal has 3 elements", array_count, 3

    Let hash_found be proc find_initializer_kind with hir1, HIR.HIR_MAP_LITERAL
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "hash literal initializer present", hash_found
    Let hash_entries be proc hir_get_map_entries from HIR with hash_found
    Let hash_count be proc list_length from List with hash_entries
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "hash literal has 2 entries", hash_count, 2

    Note: --- Stage 3: HIR -> Ruby text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_ruby_code from RubyBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced Ruby text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted Ruby is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 4: re-run the pipeline on the emitted text -> HIR2 ---
    Let hir2 be proc source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted Ruby produced HIR", hir2
    Let decls2 be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with hir2
    Let decl2_count be proc list_length from List with decls2
    proc assert_greater_than_or_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip module has declarations", decl2_count, 5

    Note: --- Stage 5: structural equality on the key constructs ---
    Let func2 be proc find_decl with hir2, HIR.HIR_FUNCTION
    Let func_kind_ok be proc same_kind with func_node, func2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves function node", func_kind_ok, 1
    Let func2_name be proc hir_get_function_name from HIR with func2
    Let func2_name_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with func2_name, "add"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves function name 'add'", func2_name_ok, 1
    Let func2_params be proc hir_get_parameters from HIR with func2
    Let func2_param_list be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with func2_params
    Let func2_param_count be proc list_length from List with func2_param_list
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 2 parameters", func2_param_count, 2

    Let if2 be proc find_decl with hir2, HIR.HIR_IF
    Let if_kind_ok be proc same_kind with if_node, if2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves if statement node", if_kind_ok, 1
    Let if2_else be proc hir_get_if_else from HIR with if2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves elsif/else tail", if2_else

    Let call_block2 be proc find_call_with_block with hir2
    Let cb_kind_ok be proc same_kind with call_block_stmt, call_block2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves block-bearing call", cb_kind_ok, 1
    Let block2 be proc find_call_block with call_block2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves trailing block", block2
    Let block2_params be proc hir_get_lambda_parameters from HIR with block2
    Let block2_param_list be proc hir_get_parameter_list from HIR with block2_params
    Let block2_param_count be proc list_length from List with block2_param_list
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves block parameter |x|", block2_param_count, 1

    Let multi2 be proc find_multiple_assign with hir2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves multiple assignment", multi2
    Let multi2_stmts be proc hir_get_block_statements from HIR with multi2
    Let multi2_count be proc list_length from List with multi2_stmts
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 2 assignment targets", multi2_count, 2

    Let array2 be proc find_initializer_kind with hir2, HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves array literal", array2
    Let array2_elems be proc hir_get_list_elements from HIR with array2
    Let array2_count be proc list_length from List with array2_elems
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 3 array elements", array2_count, 3

    Let hash2 be proc find_initializer_kind with hir2, HIR.HIR_MAP_LITERAL
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves hash literal", hash2
    Let hash2_entries be proc hir_get_map_entries from HIR with hash2
    Let hash2_count be proc list_length from List with hash2_entries
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip preserves 2 hash entries", hash2_count, 2

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process

@Reasoning:
The .each block call appears as a bare method-call statement (an expression
statement wrapping a HIR call) that carries a trailing block argument. This helper
scans declarations for the first expression statement whose inner call carries a
"ruby_call_block"-tagged argument and returns that call, distinguishing it from the
plain "puts" calls that have no block.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_call_with_block" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let decl_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl
        If decl_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_EXPR_STMT:
            Let inner be proc hir_get_expression_statement_expr from HIR with decl
            Let inner_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with inner
            If inner_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
                Let has_block be proc find_call_block with inner
                If has_block is not equal to 0:
                    Return inner
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The array and hash literals are bound as the initializer (right-hand side) of an
assignment expression statement. This helper scans declarations for the first
expression statement whose inner assignment's right-hand side is a node of the
requested kind (HIR_LIST_LITERAL or HIR_MAP_LITERAL) and returns that literal node.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_initializer_kind" takes module as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc list_length from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from List with declarations, i
        Let decl_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl
        If decl_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_EXPR_STMT:
            Let inner be proc hir_get_expression_statement_expr from HIR with decl
            Let inner_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with inner
            If inner_kind is equal to HIR.HIR_ASSIGN_EXPR:
                Let rhs be proc hir_get_assign_rhs from HIR with inner
                Let rhs_kind be proc hir_node_type from HIR with rhs
                If rhs_kind is equal to kind:
                    Return rhs
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process
